The President gave remarks at the National Museum of African American History and Culture in Washington, D.C. He praised the museum and its director, Lonnie Bunch, for their work in honoring African American heroes. He also mentioned the importance of fighting bigotry and hatred, particularly in light of recent anti-Semitic threats. The President thanked Dr. Ben Carson, who was present at the museum, and praised his achievements. He also thanked Senator Tim Scott and Alveda King for their attendance. The President expressed his desire to bring the country together and work towards justice and righteousness. He ended his remarks by congratulating the museum and thanking everyone for being there.